('13', '1', '2012-01-09 06:56:03', '2012-01-08 23:56:03', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/DSC00167.jpg\" rel=\"prettyPhoto\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-137\" title=\"DSC00167\" src=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/DSC00167-400x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI’ll take a cue from Humbert Humbert. You may hate my style, so sorry in advance.\r\n\r\nI’m a terrible sucker for melodrama, but there’s still something to be said about flying over an ocean: it’s not just time that changes; there’s a quiet moment for self-reflection; you can think clearly. You’re not here and you’re not there. Somewhere above the Pacific—or Atlantic—dwells a deep melancholy, a momentary sadness where you can think in the most clear—and perhaps literal—sense of what you’re leaving behind and what you’re going towards.  And it’s probably natural to be apprehensive: I won’t be some vacationer looking in at a culture from afar. This is a move. I’ll be home soon. Loves, it’s seven hours to Tokyo.', 'The First of Many', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-first-of-many', '', '', '2012-11-02 06:01:34', '2012-11-01 23:01:34', '', '0', 'http://www.weiluen.com/blog/?p=13', '0', 'post', '', '0'),
