('32', '1', '2012-10-24 00:00:33', '2012-10-23 17:00:33', 'Things are starting to turn a bit more normal here. But I\'m not sure what that means. I would say that I\'ve acclimated, but acclimate connotes far too positively.  And lately, acclimation seems to be my personal euphemism for a complete and total identity change. But in fairness, it\'s hard to gauge how much I\'ve changed while being here—who I was exists only as a sketchy outline, too transfigured by the nebulousness of time to ever identify in static slices. But I can still tell that I\'m different. I know that I\'ve been marooned from all the comforts of home, i.e., all the creature comforts, all of my friends, all of everything that I remember, for far too long to still be unchanged. Regardless, it doesn\'t matter. Here, there is no backwards; there is no backwards for a volunteer. You can\'t ever look behind because you\'re always charging far too rapidly forward for the muddled image left in your wake to ever be worth your consideration. What\'s left, a deceptively perfect simulacrum of home, is never real enough to justify its possible incursion into your mind and its, consequently, immuring effects. No, you can\'t be backwards looking here. You have to blaze forward so fast that you know there\'s no hope left behind you—that hope lies only in what may come. And this is why you, ever-optimistic you, try befriending the giant lizards that creep around your walls. And it\'s also why you tell yourself that giant bug swarms flew into your house back home, too.\r\n\r\nI had come here with the naive notion that I would somehow change my community for the better. No, when the score is finally tallied at the end of the game, it\'ll be sweet, capricious Thailand that\'s changed me far more than I\'d have ever dreamed of changing her.\r\n\r\nAnd even though I recognize this, even though I recognize that futility is in the augury of already-written stars, I\'m still hoping that my ambition will return.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/water-world_mg_0828_v2.jpg\" rel=\"prettyPhoto[ambition]\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-55\" title=\"water-world_mg_0828_v2\" src=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/water-world_mg_0828_v2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"660\" height=\"440\"  /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Here, I\'m reminded of a pithy truth that I seem to have forgotten:  self-actualization is awfully hard when you\'re struggling to stay afloat.</p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/wale-ambition-copy.jpg\" rel=\"prettyPhoto[ambition]\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-54\" title=\"wale-ambition-copy\" src=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/wale-ambition-copy-600x600.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"600\" /></a>', 'Ambition', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'finally-a-new-layout', '', '', '2012-11-03 18:28:24', '2012-11-03 11:28:24', '', '0', 'http://www.weiluen.com/blog/?p=32', '0', 'post', '', '0'),
