('171', '1', '2012-10-22 04:06:25', '2012-10-21 21:06:25', '&nbsp;\r\n<a href=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/DSC00167-300x225.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/DSC00167-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" title=\"DSC00167-300x225\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-14\" /></a>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI’ll take a cue from Humbert Humbert. You may hate my style, so sorry in advance.\r\n\r\nI’m a terrible sucker for melodrama, but there’s still something to be said about flying over an ocean: it’s not just time that changes; there’s a quiet moment for self-reflection; you can think clearly. You’re not here and you’re not there. Somewhere above the Pacific – or Atlantic – dwells a deep melancholy, where you can think in the most clear – and perhaps literal – sense of what you’re leaving behind and what you’re going towards.&nbsp; And it’s probably natural to be apprehensive: I won’t be some vacationer looking in at a culture from afar. This is a move. I’ll be home soon. Loves, it’s seven hours to Tokyo.', 'The First of Many', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '13-revision-9', '', '', '2012-10-22 04:06:25', '2012-10-21 21:06:25', '', '13', 'http://www.weiluen.com/blog/171', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
('73', '1', '2012-10-19 11:15:49', '2012-10-19 04:15:49', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/DSC00167-300x225.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-14 aligncenter\" title=\"DSC00167-300x225\" src=\"http://www.weiluen.com/blog/assets/DSC00167-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI’ll take a cue from Humbert Humbert. You may hate my style, so sorry in advance.\r\n\r\nI’m a terrible sucker for melodrama, but there’s still something to be said about flying over an ocean: it’s not just time that changes; there’s a quiet moment for self-reflection; you can think clearly. You’re not here and you’re not there. Somewhere above the Pacific – or Atlantic – dwells a deep melancholy, where you can think in the most clear – and perhaps literal – sense of what you’re leaving behind and what you’re going towards.  And it’s probably natural to be apprehensive: I won’t be some vacationer looking in at a culture from afar. This is a move. I’ll be home soon. Loves, it’s seven hours to Tokyo.', 'The First of Many', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '13-revision-8', '', '', '2012-10-19 11:15:49', '2012-10-19 04:15:49', '', '13', 'http://www.weiluen.com/blog/73', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
