('310', '1', '2012-11-04 15:45:41', '2012-11-04 08:45:41', '<h4>A Declaration</h4>\nI\'ve made a pledge to try and update this blog at least once per week. I\'m hoping that if I\'m at least somewhat consistent, it\'ll give me a great way to document my time over here. And to couch this in the rhetoric of productivity—I need to appease my conscience—it\'d also be a great way for me to reflect back on my week and determine what I should do going forward. Moreover, if I can maintain some modicum of honesty within the open, public framework of a blog, I might be able to gain some  insight through self-reflection.\n<h4>The Week in Reverse</h4>\nI\'ve been swamped. It\'s the first week back, so my counterparts and I have been trying to plan lessons for the next semester, trying to consolidate my projects (well, my projec<strong>t</strong>), and deal with the looming vagaries surrounding my double boss switch up. In the coming weeks, I will also be tasked with entertaining both my Peace Corps boss and my new mystery boss. In Thailand, this means lots of meetings and dinners. It also, probably, means dinner parties accompanied by Mr. Walker and his Thai pals: Blend 285, and, unbeknownst to himself, the curiously named Hong Thong. But before you misunderstand and cough <em>entitled! </em>let me explain. This will most likely require a level of Thai that would elude me even if I spent the next 100 years —because fate, kismet, whatever you like calling the ever-weaving Moirai In short, it\'s been rough, especially when you compound that with the stress of studying for an exam. And in the coming weeks, I will be tasked with entertaining both my Peace Corps boss and my new boss at site. All of this will be done at the cruel grip of , because fate, kismet, whatever you would like to call the ever-weaving Moirai,\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSo onto the main topic, we\'ve been having rolling blackouts over here. In America, we worry  about a dated power grid that could spell impending doom for the Northeast Corridor, but, here, I\'ve got two lines of unwinding cable that keep my fan powered on. No power grid problems. No worries. If there lies a luddite somewhere in the far-flung recesses of my soul, then he would probably—still, only in the quietest of voices—admit that not having technology can, possibly, provide some added value. At the very least, I can certainly take deeper breaths, now. And when I do pause to try and soak in the bucolic milieu, occasionally I catch pleasantries mixed in with the burning trash piles.\n\nIt\'s been a long week. I told myself that I would start using <a title=\"Remember The Milk\" href=\"http://jh.weiluen.com/SjW86Z\">RTM</a> (remember the milk) to organize my life. It\'s been somewhat successful. My migration from the usual google tasks isn\'t quite complete, but I\'m finding that the added plugins are highly beneficial, e.g., using <a title=\"YAR Plugin for RTM\" href=\"http://jh.weiluen.com/SjYCSM\" target=\"_blank\">YAR</a>, I\'m currently tracking the amount of time that I\'m spending on all of my activities; this lets me see a breakdown of my day in pie graph format.  And if you\'re one of those <a title=\"Wiki Getting Things DOne\" href=\"http://jh.weiluen.com/SjYN0r\" target=\"_blank\">GTD</a> (Getting Things Done) fans, RTM is completely compatible. There are also some pretty sweet plugins that allow you to directly incorporate RTM into your google apps, e.g., calendar, gmail, too.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nYes, <a title=\"Diary of a Farang\" href=\"http://jh.weiluen.com/SJ4BEp\">Tess</a>, you might\'ve been right all along: maybe more structure is helpful?', 'Heat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '303-revision-4', '', '', '2012-11-04 15:45:41', '2012-11-04 08:45:41', '', '303', 'http://www.weiluen.com/blog/310', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
('311', '1', '2012-11-05 06:16:31', '2012-11-04 23:16:31', '<p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Lesson Title: \n</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Date: </strong> Aug 27, 2012 <strong>                Duration: 08:30-11.30\n</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Teacher(s): </strong><em>\n			</em></span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Learning Objectives: </strong>By the end of this lesson, Student will be able to:\n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    1. ask and answer yes/no question .\n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    2. write this sentence \"Is he/she __adjective__?\"\n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    3.\n</span></p><p>\n </p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Materials and Resources:\n</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    Facilitator Materials:\n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    • olor cards\n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    • Papers\n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    • \n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    Supplies:\n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">    • worksheet\n</span></p><p>\n </p><p>\n </p><p>\n </p><p>\n </p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Implementation Outline:\n</strong></span></p><div><table style=\"border-collapse:collapse\" border=\"0\"><colgroup><col style=\"width:158px\"/><col style=\"width:458px\"/></colgroup><tbody valign=\"top\"><tr><td style=\"padding-left: 7px; padding-right: 7px; border-top:  solid black 0.5pt; border-left:  solid black 0.5pt; border-bottom:  solid black 0.5pt; border-right:  solid black 0.5pt\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Lesson Segments and Materials Used:</strong></span> </p></td><td style=\"padding-left: 7px; padding-right: 7px; border-top:  solid black 0.5pt; border-left:  none; border-bottom:  solid black 0.5pt; border-right:  solid black 0.5pt\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Activities, Techniques and Instructional Sequence:</strong></span> </p></td></tr><tr><td style=\"padding-left: 7px; padding-right: 7px; border-top:  none; border-left:  solid black 0.5pt; border-bottom:  solid black 0.5pt; border-right:  solid black 0.5pt\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>I. Motivation\n</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>( _30_minutes)\n</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><em>Materials and\n</em></span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><em>Handouts:\n</em></span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong><br/>Preparation of hangman</strong></span></p></td><td style=\"padding-left: 7px; padding-right: 7px; border-top:  none; border-left:  none; border-bottom:  solid black 0.5pt; border-right:  solid black 0.5pt\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\">      Review: Teacher asks students to play \"Hangman game\" about occupations (Divide students into 2 teams) following worksheet.\n</span></p><p><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt\"><strong>Split the class into two teams. Make a list of vocabulary new vocab for students. Plan out professions. Sight words and alphabet. \n</strong></span></p><p>\n </p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman\"><strong>\n									</strong>Teacher asks 